  "summary": "Hercule Poirot concludes that Robin Upward killed his mother, Mrs. Uppward, noting that the killer's arrogance and the deliberate arrangement of \"props\" at the scene allowed the crime to occur despite Mrs. Oliver being nearby. Poirot then confronts Miss Williams, revealing that she is actually Maud Craig, the daughter of Eve Kane. Maud explains that she sought revenge after discovering that Eve Kane had not died in Australia as believed, but had instead become the wealthy and arrogant Mrs. Uppward. Maud had taken a job to investigate and had gone to the house with a gun to confront her, only to find Mrs. Uppward already dead. Poirot decides not to take action against her.\n\nIn an epilogue, Poirot and Superintendent Spence celebrate the case's resolution at a restaurant. Spence notes that Robin Upward's confession was facilitated by his own cowardice and the lack of evidence. They discuss other characters, including Mrs. Carpenter, whose shady past as a cabaret dancer led her to hide her true status, and the Weatherby family, whose conflicts are driven by money. Poirot reveals he is meddling in the lives of Dierdre Henderson and James Bentley, hoping to arrange their marriage. \n\nThe conversation shifts to Dr. Lund, whom Spence reveals was once accused of poisoning his first wife via anonymous letters. Poirot realizes this explains why Dr. Lund attempted to push him under a train, as the doctor feared Poirot was investigating him. The passage concludes with Spence confirming that Robin Upward will be tried for murder the following week.",
